did.head: Papers Summary
did.abstract: The Browning W. Ware papers contain the materials of noted Texas pastor Browning W. Ware, who was best known for leading First Baptist Church, Austin Texas, and many other religious and civic organizations.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: Browning Worth Ware, longtime pastor, author, and church leader, was an important contemporary of Baptist figures Foy Valentine, Charles Wellborn, and other Southern Baptist leaders. Ware pastored Texas churches in Beaumont, Denton, Cleburne, Hubbard, Satin, and Austin, and wrote a column called "Diary of a Modern Pilgrim" that ran in the Austin-American Statesman and other newspapers for over 40 years.

Ware was born in Fort Worth, Texas, on 1928 November 5 to J.W. and Myrtle Haralson Ware. The oldest of five children, Browning Ware attended Woodrow Wilson High School in Dallas, Texas, then went to Baylor University. He graduated from Baylor with a B.A. and Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary with a B.D. and Th.D.

Browning Ware married twice, first to Corinne S. Ware in 1950. They had three children together: Brooks Browning Ware, Suzanne Ware Luper, and Camille Ware Kress. Browning and Corinne Ware divorced in 1985. Ware married Juanell Wright Ware in 1987.

He was best-known for his 20 years of service at the then-1,700 member First Baptist Church in Austin, Texas. Along with leading pastoral ministries, he also served in the community, including with the Austin Ethics Commission, Cystic Fibrosis Foundation, and various mental health organizations. His weekly column "Diary of a Modern Pilgrim" was run in multiple newspapers throughout the state, but was especially well-known in the Austin-American Statesman. On the state and national levels, he was an active leader in what later became the Baptist General Convention of Texas, the Southern Baptist Convention, and was Chaplain of the Texas House and Senate for fourteen years.

After many years of dedicated service to God and the people of his church and community, Browning Ware passed away from cancer on 2002 November 1. He is buried in the Texas State Cemetery in Austin, Texas.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The Browning W. Ware papers documents the efforts of Browning W. Ware as he led Baptist churches throughout Texas. It also contains materials on civic organizations Ware was involved in, as well as personal and university-related papers. Topics represented in the collection include Baptist life as a pastor in Texas, Ware's studies at Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary, his work in various civic organizations in Austin, Texas, general Baptist materials, and other topics. Material types include correspondence, literary productions, printed materials, financial documents, and others. Formats represented in the collection include photographs, 2 color slides, and a large number of phonodiscs.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The Browning W. Ware papers were organized by subject, type, and function prior to this finding aid. Most materials were in folders with titles, but some folders did not have titles. Original order was maintained as much as possible. The level of processing deemed appropriate for this collection differs from other record groups at The Texas Collection.

Currently, the Browning W. Ware papers are arranged in six series: I. Pastoral Life, II. "Diary of a Modern Pilgrim" Articles, III. Personal Materials, IV. University Studies, V. Sermons, VI. Audio Records.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series contains materials from Browning Ware's long service as a Baptist pastor. Much of what he wrote was not able to be traced to a specific church that he pastored, especially since he preached so often at neighboring church services and revivals.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series contains sermons authored by Dr. Browning Ware, through the different churches he served and the various revivals and other speaking engagements he did that required sermons. Also included are inspirational stories and notes that Ware drew content or inspiration from for his sermons, and some sermons not by Browning Ware that nevertheless influenced his sermons.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series contains a specialized kind of LP record produced using a Gray Audograph machine, and audio cassette tapes. Recorded on this media are Browning Ware's sermons for select years. Many of these sermons, but not all of them, have been transcribed.
